pbel","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Cambell","meanings":["(1997: 229;2007: 1415; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campell","meanings":["(2007: 398; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: variant of   Campbell   (see also   Camel  )."]},{"name":"Beauchamp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."]},{"name":"Camel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Napoleon, Patrice.","English (of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Norman French <i>came(i)l</i> ‘camel’ (from Latin <i>camelus</i>, classical Greek <i>kamēlos</i>), possibly denoting a clumsy person or someone with long legs. It may also be a topographic or habitational name referring to a house with a sign depicting a camel (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English); compare 5 below.","English: possibly a habitational name from Queen Camel and West Camel in Somerset, early recorded as <i>Camel(le)</i>, possibly a Celtic name from <i>canto-</i> ‘border, district’ and <i>mēl</i> ‘bare hill’."]}]},{"name":"Dugald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Dubhghall .  The final <i>-d</i> is due to a mishearing of the Gaelic form, in which the final <i>-ll</i> sounds like <i>-ld</i> to English ears."],"variants":[{"name":"Dougal","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Dubhghall ."]},{"name":"Dubhghall","meanings":["Gaelic: from <i>dubh</i> ‘black, dark’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’. This was a byname applied to Danes, in contrast to the fairer Norwegians and Icelanders (  compare  Fionnghall  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dugald Campbell IV Laird of Craignish was born about 1225, in Craignish, Argyll, Scotland, his father, Dugald \"Duncan\" Campbell III Laird Craignish, was 27 and his mother, Miss McSween, was 27. He married Jennet Lamont about 1245, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1225–":"umbes 1225–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1265–1309":"1265–1309","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1250–1290":"1250–1290","1199–1250":"1199–1250","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","ABT    1245":"umbes 1245","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1199":"1199","about 1225":"umbes 1225","about 1245":"umbes 1245","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1309":"1309","Craignish, Argyllshire, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Scotland","of Craignish,Lochow,Argyllshire,Scotland":"Craignish Castle, Argyll and Bute, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1225–":"noin 1225–Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1225–Female":"1225–Kuollut","1265–1309":"1265–1309","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1250–1290":"1250–1290","1199–1250":"1199–1250","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","about 1260":"noin 1260","ABT    1245":"noin 1245","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1199":"1199","a